.Dd April 11, 2026
.Dt FLASH 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm flash
.Nd simple plaintext flashcard tool
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl h
.Nm
.Op Fl p
.Nm
.Op Fl r
.Ar deck ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a simple plain text flashcard tool for X.
It reads decks in the form
.Dq question:::answer
and shows one card at a time in a centered X11 window.
.Pp
If
.Fl p
is given,
.Nm
prints the LLM deck-generation prompt compiled from
.Pa PROMPT.txt
and exits.
.Pp
When a deck contains stack separators of the form
.Dq \&\#\ SEP timestamp success/attempt[/total] ,
.Nm
studies only the bottom stack, meaning the cards directly above the last
separator.
The separator metadata belongs to the layer above it.
The optional third number is written only when not all cards in that layer were
attempted.
At the end of the run it rewrites that separator and, if needed, appends a new
bottom retry layer followed by a trailing
.Dq \&\#\ SEP .
.Pp
Closing the window without pressing
.Sy p ,
.Sy x ,
or
.Sy Escape
uses the compile-time
.Va closemode
from
.Pa config.h .
.Pp
If
.Fl r
is given,
.Nm
first drops every layer below the top one before studying.
.Pp
If
.Fl h
is given,
.Nm
prints usage information and exits.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl h
Print usage information and exit.
.It Fl p
Print the compiled-in LLM deck-generation prompt and exit.
.It Fl r
Reset each deck back to its top layer before studying.
.El
.Sh USAGE
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Em Keyboard commands
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy Space
Flip the current card.
.It Sy j
Mark the current card remembered and go to the next card after it has been
flipped once.
.It Sy k
Mark the current card failed and go to the next card after it has been flipped
once.
.It Sy p
Quit early and save failed cards plus unseen cards.
.It Sy x
Quit early and save only cards explicitly marked failed.
.It Sy Escape
Quit immediately without saving.
.El
.El
.Sh FORMAT
A deck file is made of one flashcard per line:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
What does CPU stand for?:::Central Processing Unit
2 + 2:::4
.Ed
.Pp
To store retry stacks inside the same file,
.Nm
also accepts separator lines:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
\&\#\ SEP 2026-04-11T22:00:00 3/5
\&\#\ SEP 2026-04-11T22:00:00 1/2/3
\&\#\ SEP
.Ed
.Sh CUSTOMIZATION
.Nm
can be customized by creating a custom config.h and (re)compiling the
source code.
This keeps it fast, secure and simple.
